Wash and dry produce.

Dice @Tomato{1} into ¼-inch pieces. Peel and mince or grate @Garlic{1%clove}. Drain @Black Beans{1%unit}.

In a #medium pot{} (large pot for 4 servings), combine @White Rice{1/2%cup}, tomato, garlic, beans, @Chicken Stock Concentrate{1}, ¾ cup water, @Fajita Spice Blend{1%tsp} (you'll use more later), and a pinch of @salt{}. Bring to a boil, then cover and reduce to a low simmer.

Cook until rice is tender, ~{20-22%minutes}.

Keep covered off heat until ready to serve.

While rice cooks, roughly chop @Cilantro{1/4%oz}. Quarter @Lime{1}.

In a #small bowl{}, combine @Sour Cream{1.5%tbsp}, cilantro, and juice from one lime wedge (two wedges for 4 servings). Add @water{} 1 tsp at a time until mixture reaches a drizzling consistency. Taste and season with @salt{} and @Pepper{} if desired.

Pat @Pork Chops{10%oz} dry with paper towels and season all over with 1 tsp Fajita Spice Blend (2 tsp for 4 servings), salt, and pepper. (Use the rest of the Fajita Spice Blend as you like.)

Heat a drizzle of @Cooking Oil{1%tsp} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add pork and cook until browned and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes} per side.

> TIP: If pork starts to brown too quickly, lower the heat and cover pan.

Transfer to a #cutting board{} to rest.

Fluff rice and beans with a #fork{} and stir in @Butter{1%tbsp} (2 TBSP for 4 servings).

Slice pork crosswise.

Divide rice and beans and pork between plates in separate sections. Pour any resting juices over pork and drizzle with crema. Serve with any remaining lime wedges on the side.

> Pork is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.